Nations in temperate zones enjoy well-balanced atmosphere—proportionate stature, civilized habits, good disposition.

Eclipse duration in hours equals years (solar) or months (lunar) of effect.

Human-shaped signs (Gemini, Virgo, Aquarius) indicate effects will fall upon the human race.
Tropical signs = atmospheric changes; Northern signs = earthquakes; Southern signs = floods.

Saturn causes destruction by cold, long illnesses, consumption, decay, poverty, and exile.
Mars causes wars, seditions, drought, fevers, sudden deaths, and murders.
Eclipse colours indicate planetary nature: black=Saturn, white=Jupiter, red=Mars.
The new moon preceding Sun's Aries entry indicates the year's general atmospheric constitution.

Monthly atmospheric constitutions predicted from each new and full moon—angular planets and aspects examined.

Material fortune is judged from the Part of Fortune, its rulers, and the Moon's configurations.
Rank is determined by the luminaries' angular position and their planetary attendants.
Profession is determined by the planet ruling the mid-heaven—each planet governs specific trades.
Employment quality determined by oriental planet or MC ruler—Mercury for writing, Venus for arts, Mars for manual work.

Saturn aspect = elderly spouse; Jupiter = wealthy/noble; Mars = bold/violent.

Life requires that we have a personality—and a personality is always a role we play, always less than what we truly are. A personality is always a mask.
Second-house influences create a crisis of self-respect. And the way we choose to resolve that insecurity becomes a key life theme.
Let's call the third house the House of Perception, remembering always that perception flows two ways: we gather information from the world and then we echo it back again.
The fourth house is the most subjective of the twelve. The arena it represents is a secret one. No one outside ourselves can see it.
Joy—how deeply we need it! Its absence is as fatal as a ten-year fast or a month without oxygen. Without that sparkle, we wither.
Now, we ourselves are the servant. But not in any degrading sense. In this house we recognize an elemental human need: the desire to exercise competence and to be recognized for it.
Aries is a newborn tumbling into physical existence. Every cell screaming: 'Am I going to make it?' Fear of annihilation: the basic Arian experience.
The Bull. Ancient, immovable as the mountain, still as a forest at evening. Taurus has come to build essence into form—creating sacred physical space through patience and craft.
The Twins. Gemini has come into the world to witness—experiencing life from multiple perspectives, tasting all life has to offer without clinging to any single viewpoint.
Jupiter is the Great Benefic—the planet of faith, expansion, and wisdom. It's the largest planet yet moves with surprising speed, symbolizing magnitude and momentum.

Jupiter is the planet of faith. Not necessarily religious faith—although that's one possibility. More fundamentally, Jupiter represents our capacity to believe that life has meaning, that the future holds promise, that we are part of something larger than ourselves.
Mars is the warrior—our capacity for assertive action, for overcoming obstacles, for courage under fire.
Saturn is the Great Malefic—the planet of discipline, limitation, and time. Its 29.5 year orbit symbolizes patience, sustained effort, and the long game.
Uranus is the planet of individuality, rebellion, and freedom beyond Saturn's structures. It belongs to the "invisible planets"—requiring conscious work for constructive expression.
Neptune represents consciousness-beyond-ego—the function that decentralizes the sense of "I" and opens awareness to a larger field. It orients the mind toward myth rather than concrete viewpoints.

Pluto represents destiny, power, and existential transformation. It takes us to the icy edge of the solar system where sun and earth shrink to insignificance, confronting us with life's apparent futility.
The Crab. A creature with a hard shell protecting a soft interior. Cancer has come into the world to create sanctuary—to build a place of safety, nurturing, and belonging.
The Lion. Regal, confident, living boldly and warmly from the heart. Leo has come to shine—to radiate inner light through creative self-expression and generous celebration of life.
The Virgin. Not asexual, but self-complete—choosing to serve from fullness, not lack. Virgo brings practical precision, humble craftsmanship, and refinement to whatever it touches.
Conjunction is not addition but multiplication—the planets amplify each other's expression, for better or worse.
Conjunctions often represent blind spots because the functions are so merged the person may not recognize the fusion.
The opposition demands we own both ends—recognizing that the "other person's" qualities are our own disowned aspects.
Opposition is fundamentally a relationship aspect—the people we attract often carry our disowned planets.
If opposition is the aspect of rivals, square is the aspect of natural enemies who cannot even comprehend each other's language.
The square's gift is growth through friction—forcing psychological work that produces character strength after struggle.
Because trines feel good, we take them for granted—the gift becomes wasted potential when neglected.
Once activated through conscious effort, trines carry us further than any square with far less effort.
Sextiles connect compatible but different elements (Fire-Air, Earth-Water), creating stimulating exchange rather than fusion.
The Scales. Libra has come to learn the art of partnership—not just romantic, but harmonious mutually beneficial relationships where both parties grow.
The Scorpion/Eagle/Phoenix. Scorpio has come to master transformation—learning nothing lasts forever, all forms dissolve, in dissolution lies renewal seed.
The Archer (Centaur). Sagittarius has come to discover meaning—not just information but larger patterns, philosophical frameworks, truth giving life purpose.
The Mountain Goat. Capricorn has come to achieve mastery—build something enduring, earn recognition through accomplishment, reach top through merit.
The Water-Bearer (knowledge carrier). Aquarius has come to achieve freedom—psychological liberation from tribal conditioning, autonomy to be completely oneself.
Two Fishes in opposite directions—but the Ocean itself: the infinite, boundless, source of all life. Pisces has come to experience transcendence—realize world is construct of consciousness.
Mercury is the planet in charge of the library we keep in our heads. Its function is to think, to know, to deduce, to reason. This is the planet of the mind, of the linear, logical functions.
Venus is the planet of love, beauty, and values—the function that creates relationships and appreciates aesthetics. It represents the capacity to connect not from neediness but from appreciation.
Mars is the warrior of the birthchart—the planet of action, courage, will, and desire. It enables decisive action and overcoming obstacles through directed force.

The sun is the gravitational center of the human personality—the focal point of all varied functions that coexist in each person: our sense of identity, of being a distinct person with certain ways of feeling and seeing.
The moon symbolizes feelings. Its most striking quality is variability—always changing, always passing through phases. Luna symbolizes the part of consciousness that reacts and responds.

Identification—putting yourself in the other person's shoes—is the cornerstone of all dramatic art and the basis of any intimate relationship. If the mind fails to set up that elemental I-equal-you equation, no human being will ever touch us.

Sex, death, and the occult—in each we confront one of the basic givens of human life. In each we confront needs and issues that release intense and disruptive emotional energies into consciousness. In each we meet an instinct.
All our views of reality are conditioned by an unspoken model of the world—and that model is always arbitrary and limiting.

The midheaven represents how we look to people who do not know us. They see us, not as people, but as embodiments of various functions in society. Depersonalized. Representative of a class. They see our status.
Direction. That is the essence of eleventh-house terrain. Where are you going? What are you becoming? What are the hopes and dreams and aspirations that give meaning to your daily life?

Whenever trouble strikes, each of us has a built-in escape route. We can move our attention away from the dramas of personality. We can focus it on a peaceful place deep within us, a place that is always there, waiting.
People change—the assumption that they do not is a lie running through most astrological writing.
Seasonal changes, not stars, are at the heart of sign symbolism—through variations in light we mark four critical points that divide the circle into Fire, Earth, Air, and Water.

The south node represents the past and its effects on us; the north node represents the future toward which we are being drawn—always in opposition, symbolizing tension between what we have been and what we must become.

Archaic astrology was locality-centered, bounded by the horizon of a particular place, reflecting tribal consciousness rooted in the soil.
The four angles create the 'cross of matter,' the cardinal points that are the most powerful positions in any natal chart.
Monotheistic astrology treats the Sun as singular divine source, with twelve signs representing twelve "soul avenues" for individual spiritual development in dialogue with one divinity.
The first house, marked by the Ascendant, represents the point of birth and the dawn of consciousness. It governs self-image, personality expression, and how others perceive you upon first encounter.
The body is the first and fundamental possession of the self—it provides the means for actualizing potentialities inherent in selfhood.
Intelligence is the capacity to come to terms with any environment—first physical, then psychic—and to adjust to its demands and eventually transform it.
In the fourth house the person should reach the experience of center—the center of his own total personality as well as the center of global humanity.
Creativity is referred to the fifth house because to create is to impress upon one's community characteristics of one's own personality—to make one's mark upon society.
The sixth house represents everything dealing with personal crises and shows how an individual can grow and become transformed.
The seventh house deals with experiences based upon sustained modes of relationship—the cooperators should feel their operation serves a purpose within a larger unit.
The eighth house refers to the possessions of the relationship—what is available to become an operative factor in society, based on trust, management, and responsibility.
Ninth house experiences are those encountered in the search for the meaning of things—understanding is a holistic process implying the experience of a people and their culture.
The tenth house is the house of achievement—first house potential theoretically becomes actualized fully here through integration into the greater whole.
In the eleventh house the power of society is released through the individual—it is creation not of the individual but through them, as the Whole works through a clear lens.
The twelfth house closes the cycle—the individual either consolidates successes into seed for new cycle, or meets accumulated results of failures as Guardian of the Threshold.

The twelve houses are classified into three groups: Angular houses (1,4,7,10) represent action and initiative; Succedent houses (2,5,8,11) represent consolidation and substance; Cadent houses (3,6,9,12) represent distribution and transition.
One cannot separate the way one sees oneself from the manner in which one meets people—selfhood and relationship are interdependent aspects of one fundamental drive.
Each 28-year cycle represents passage through all twelve houses at a distinct level: physical (0-28), psychomental (28-56), spiritual (56-84).
